Five truths about terrorism.
SAO PAULO – American politics are held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or about 16% of the population, now ranked terrorism as the country's top problem – a 3% increase in just one month.
For the past decade, no Americans had been as concerned about terrorism, even if their numbers are still far below the 46% recorded in the aftermath of the 9/11 attacks.
The consequences of this evolution in public opinion were most felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
The candidacy of Donald Trump, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is notably inflamed (if not incendiary), undoubtedly profited from it.
Some politicians authorise themselves to speak of the battle against terrorism as of the "Third World War".
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the attack in San Bernardino, California, in December of last year.
But the candidates in the presidential election, like some media, followers of the old adage "if it bleeds, it makes the front page," have exaggerated the proportions.
To put terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – like others – keep the following considerations in mind.
Terrorism is a form of theatre.
Terrorists worry more about holding attention and dominating political news than the number of their victims itself.
The Islamic State (IS) takes great care with its staging.
Brutal beheadings broadcast on social media are intended to destabilize and scandalize – and consequently to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating the consequences and making headlines with each terrorist action is playing into the terrorists' hands.
Terrorism is not the most serious threat weighing on the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills significantly fewer people than road accidents or smoking.
From this point of view, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
It's more likely to be struck by lightning than to be killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen is killed by a terrorist is, according to experts, one in 3.5 million.
Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (a one in 950,000 chance), from an appliance accident (a one in 1.5 million chance), by a deer or a moose crossing the road (a one in 2 million chance), or in a commercial plane crash (a one in 2.9 million chance).
Six thousand Americans die behind the wheel every year while texting or talking on their mobile phones.
It's many hundreds of times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks committed by disgruntled employees or mass shootings at universities or schools.
Terrorism is not World War Three.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a terrorist flare-up.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement assassinated a certain number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
In the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, both from the "autonomous" left, hijacked planes outside national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political leaders (as well as ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon draped in a religious cloak.
Many of their leaders are not traditional fundamentalists, but people whose identity has been destroyed by globalization, who are looking for meaning in the imaginary and purely communal world of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of ISIS limits its field of attraction.
His sectarian attacks already prevent him from addressing all Muslims, all the more so Hindus, Christians or other believers.
The ISIS will ultimately be defeated, just as the previous transnational terrorist groups that preceded it were.
Terrorism is like jiu-jitsu.
The weaker of the two opponents uses the strength of the stronger to defeat it.
No terrorist organisation has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have succeeded in overthrowing one.
But if they manage to shock and provoke the citizens of a state enough to push them to futile actions, they may hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda managed to lure Americans to Afghanistan.
ISIS was born from the rubble of the US-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, we need smart power.
An intelligent power is capable of associating the coercive power (hard power) of the army and the police with the influence power (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
The influence is also necessary in terms of power if one wants to vaccinate those on the periphery and the irreconcilables who seek to recruit.
That's why attention paid to the account of events and the way US action is commented on social media is just as important and necessary as precision airstrikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points a finger at Muslims and alienates the goodwill that could allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
The anti-Islam stance of some of the current presidential candidates is so counter-productive.
The terrorist question is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, of our armed forces and of our diplomacy.
She constitutes an important piece of our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep out of reach of terrorists weapons of mass destruction.
But we must not fall into the trap set by the terrorists.
Let's not fill the theater where actions carried out by thugs and hoodlums take place.
If we abandon the main stage of our public discourse to them, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and reveal our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
